Tavares but also tells a larger story about postcolonial nation building, musical activism, and diaspora life within the Lusophone sphere. It follows the parallel trajectories of Cabo Verdean independence and Tavares's musical career over four decades (1975-2010). Tavares lived and worked in Cabo Verde, Portugal, and the United States, where he died in New Bedford, Massachusetts at age fifty-four. Tavares's music serves as a lens through which we can view Cabo Verde's transition from a Portuguese colony to an independent, democratic nation, one that was shaped in part through the musician's persistent humanitarian messages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusiciansvBiographyzCabo Verde. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismzCabo Verde. 0aPopular musicxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryzCabo Verde. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryzCabo Verde. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh  aCabo Verde.  aDemocratic Republic.  aDiaspora Life.  aHumanitarian.  aIsland Nation.  aLusophone Sphere.  aMusical Activism.  aMusician.  aPortuguese Colony.  aTransition.1 aAmado, Abel Djassi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800103979?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800103979423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800103979/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles